{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bef269fc-0859-415a-9560-a3b34929d29b","content":"Yes, these are **known MSTest v4 runtime behavioral changes** that compile cleanly but break at runtime:\n\n## 1. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it no longer has a meaningful `TestName` (it's `null`). Previously in v3 it was populated with the first test's name. Accessing it now throws or returns null.\n\n**Fix:** Don't rely on `TestContext.TestName` in `ClassInitialize`. If you need it for logging, use the class name instead:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassSetup(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is null in v4 for class-level context\n    var name = context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName;\n    System.Console.WriteLine($\"Setting up for: {name}\");\n}\n```\n\n## 2. Discovery errors\n\nIn MSTest v4, **test discovery is stricter**. Common causes:\n\n- The `TestContext` property **must be non-nullable or have a default**. MSTest v4 requires it to be settable but may warn/error if nullable annotations conflict.\n- More importantly, if `ClassInitialize` **throws** (which yours does due to the null `TestName` access), it can cascade into discovery failures for all tests in that class.\n\n**Fix your `ClassInitialize`** (above), and the discovery errors should resolve.\n\nWould you like me to apply these fixes to your files?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fd3962f3-70b6-4dc1-b339-7939737a7fd5","outputTokens":372,"requestId":"4812:6BE2:21BFBF:267244:69FC049F"},"id":"384a1fe6-2427-4e58-bcd7-aee2192c7c13","timestamp":"2026-05-07T03:19:07.231Z","parentId":"81fefd69-88b4-4f6c-94fc-1c89bec301c7"}
